				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{Percentage}}\,{\mathrm{of}}\,{\mathrm{variance}}\,{\mathrm{explained}}\left( {R^2} \right) = \frac{{{\mathrm{BSS}}}}{{{\mathrm{WSS}} + {\mathrm{BSS}}}}$$\end{document}PercentageofvarianceexplainedR2=BSSWSS+BSSwhere BSS (between sum of squares) is the between-groups variance in Spearman distances and WSS (within sum of squares) is the within-groups variance in Spearman distances. We used two criteria to choose the value Kx for which the variance explained reaches a plateau, that is, there is no additional gain in information (R2) when using the next clustering Kx + 1 (Figure S1). The criteria used to choose Kx were (1) the “Elbow” (or “knee”) method25 and (2) the pseudo F-index58. Both criteria indicated an optimal and stable number of clusters, Kx = 29 (Figure S1).
